Mostly dark throat “dribbling” into upper breast with small white chin. Bold, extensive breast band on slightly rufous-tinged breast/belly. Often perched directly on thin power lines; perhaps a soft ID feature of northern birds, which are accustomed to perching delicately atop firs. Possibly a returning bird that spent last winter here: https://ebird.org/checklist/S76590573. Photos

It's been years since I last had opportunity to study one of these RTHA subspecies, so now looking forward to seeing more of these.  This bird was perched on poles on the eastern edge of the fish ponds. The Handbook of Texas Birds regards B.j. fuertesi as an uncommon resident in central Texas.

Buteo with blackish body and light gray/white flight feathers and tail. I noted no obvious red/pink color to tail which could be more suggestive of a dark morph Calurus subspecies.  I also considered dark morph Rough-legged Hawk.  However this bird was soaring with 2 other eastern Red-tailed Hawks all 3 appearing to have similar body shape/size. I also noticed no obvious darker/larger terminal band to suggest dark morph Rough-legged Hawk. Observed this bird in flight well with 10x binoculars. I noted no warm brown coloration to the head that is suggested in some photos. This appears to be attributed to the lighting of sun exposure to the head but not the underparts and poor quality photos. Continued in flight to the NW and out of sight with the other 2 Red-tailed Hawks. Did not appear to be staying around the airport.

Stocky buteo shape, dark brown overall head, throat and breast from front view, with small paler curved bill.  Bird took off as we approached, 2 tone wings similar to a TUVU, with brown patagials above a white band and dark edge, wingtips/fingers. Tail was not rufous, but brown and white streaked with thick white band from below.

Observation Details: Pictures 2,3,4 are of the second Abieticola.  This second Abieticola has a dark malar area/head/nape, large belly band and rufous throat "dribbles".  The large belly band is not as heavily marked/ the throat is not solid/dark as more heavily marked Abieticolas that I have reported previously.  I do not recollect seeing/photographing this migrant, and because the belly band was not as extensively marked/ and throat was not solid/dark, I sent these photos our for review (to those more experienced with this subspecies) and this was the response- if the identification was based only on the belly band, the identification would be left as RTHA, but, the throat, breast streaking, and marked underwings with nearly complete lining of black herringbone is enough abieticola for me".

Locality: Fox Hollow Subdivision Park and Pond

Observation Details: Having not seen such dark markings before, I asked if this plumage was more common in red-tailed hawks. This response came from an expert on a raptor ID group: "This is a juvenile by the monochromatic brown tones, spotted bellyband and lack of dark terminal band on the wings. Red-tailed Hawk by dark patagials, white chest with bellyband. As a juvenile there is more overlap in phenotype than in adults, and often we can not identify them to subspecies level. As such, this bird could be either a slightly heavier marked eastern (borealis) or a northern (abieticola). To me it is not heavily enough marked to be a slam dunk abieticola and I would probably not assign a subspecies to it."

Media notes: This wing-tagged hawk (D2) was captured at Portland Int'l. Airport in July 2021 and released in Halfway, OR. (Info. rec'd. from an Oregon Aviation Wildlife Technician.)
Observation Details: As I was walking back along the levee, two buteos came flying in from the east. At the time I thought both were RSH’s, but now I think the first one was a RSH and the second one a RTH. The RTH perched in a eucalyptus tree on the far side of the north ditch. It had conspicuous orange wing-tags on both wings. The left tag read D2 or DZ. I did a Google search and found a website to report wing-tagged raptors.  I submitted a report.  On November 23, I received an e-mail reply from Erick Shore, Aviation Wildlife Technician for the Port of Portland in Oregon: “The code you saw was most likely D2, which is a red-tailed hawk that was first captured at Portland International Airport earlier this year in July.  It was released in Halfway, OR and your sighting is the first we’ve received since then.  It’s good to hear that it is still alive and well. “Once again, thank you for taking the time to send us a report. We truly appreciate your participation and with the help of individuals such as you, we are able to determine the most successful release sites. This in turn helps to reduce the number of birds returning to PDX and contributes to a safer airfield for both people and birds.”   On November 24, I received this additional information From Carole Hallett, the Wildlife Biologist who did the banding: “This bird was one of two fledglings from a nest very close to the airport (PDX). D2's dad (8J) has been with this nesting territory since 2011 and his mom (unbanded) for only about 3 years. We caught D2 and his brother (D1) on the airfield when they were young fledglings. Because they were still dependent on their parents at this age rather than take them for release right away they were held  for a time in a huge flight cage under the care of our local Audubon Wildlife Care Center. Once they were ready to go  they were banded and tagged and released out near Halfway. You spotted him 85 days later ~560 miles SSE from the release site. That's a long way! He is one of fewer than maybe a dozen or so PDX red-tails that have re-sighted down in CA in over twenty years of banding. Good spotting.”

Stuff only started to move until the late afternoon today (only 7 RTHA in 70 minutes of HW this morning) but oh boy did it move. Lots of birds coming in from the NW today, and in particularly large kettles. Our tally was: 3, 4, 2, 15, 5, 23, 3, 8, 2, 3, 1, 1, 1, 3, 2, 4, 1, 6, 3, 2, 1. Seven were dark morphs (5 adults and 2 juveniles); 3 were intermediate (all adults); and the rest were light morphs. One of the dark morphs is a strong candidate for Harlan's but I will have to review the photos. The larger concentrations were typically all juveniles, and the singles and pairs were typically adults. About 1/5 of the raptors also working "the gap" which is the flyway directly east of my location. The winds started out in the N/NW but moved more and more west as the day went on. Overall great movement and this is probably the last weekend of good hawk numbers before they rapidly decline for winter.

Observation Details: I was just informed by David Rankin that I was wrong on this bird. David is pretty sure that it is a Dark-morphed Red-tailed Hawk and not a Dark-morphed Ferruginous Hawk.    I caught this bird hovering way over the area drifting away from the area as I pulled up to the site. I was only able to get these few pictures. As I pulled up, I stupidly just thought "oh a Turkey Vulture" and wasted a good 15 seconds before I suddenly realized with my naked eye that it was not a Turkey Vulture.   I then quickly got out my camera and got these few distant flight pictures as it was drifting away. It does not seem to be a "Zone-tailed Hawk". My "Stokes" bird book has a Dark-morphed Ferruginous Hawk picture that sure looks like this bird, based on the under wings and tail pattern so that is what I initially posted. I have now changed it to a Dark-morphed Red-tailed Hawk.

Media notes: Strange RTHA, but definitely a Calurus
Observation Details: Tally: 3, 2, 1, 1, 2, 5, 11, 7, 4, 3, 2, 1, 3, 4, 1, 5, 17, 15, 4, 3, 2, 1, 1, 2, 5, 2, 3, 2, 1, 4, 3, 1, 8, 2, 1, 1, 1  Spectacular movement of RTHA. A couple of nice kettles too. Birds started coming from directly north before quickly shifting eastwards. It stayed east for about 40 minutes before switching west and then north again. The RTHA would kettle over Bernal and then explode into individual birds... and then float down towards me. Additionally, the raven's were fairly aggressive today so I got a good 20 birds from just raven mobs. Two of the kettles had a sharpie, one had a merlin, one had a shouldy, and one had a roughie. I tried to pick out other buteos and Harlan's to no avail. I managed to confirm around 90% of the birds as the calurus ssp. There was a very rusty colored dark morph and a buffy intermediate morph, but every single other bird was a light morph. Additionally, one juvenile RTHA had extensive banding on the primaries sort of like a Harlan's but the overall appearance is diagnostic for calurus, see the photo below. Really happy with the count today!

Observation Details: first seen feeding on a hunter's butchered deer carcass. It hopped into the woods as we approached and then continued hopping further into the woods.  Since it did not fly we decided it was possibly injured and we should attempt to capture and take to rehab.  We didn't see any sign of injury.  We called the rehabber and she asked the situation and suggested that perhaps it had eaten too much and could not yet fly. She instructed us to observe it for an hour to see if it recovered. We took it to my backyard and it recovered in about 20 minutes and eventually flew off. Tail was gray and not red suggesting a young bird. Was surprised that the bird in hand was rather small, despite its appearance.

Media notes: 16 of the 23 in this particular kettle
Observation Details: Stuff only started to move until the late afternoon today (only 7 RTHA in 70 minutes of HW this morning) but oh boy did it move. Lots of birds coming in from the NW today, and in particularly large kettles. Our tally was: 3, 4, 2, 15, 5, 23, 3, 8, 2, 3, 1, 1, 1, 3, 2, 4, 1, 6, 3, 2, 1. Seven were dark morphs (5 adults and 2 juveniles); 3 were intermediate (all adults); and the rest were light morphs. One of the dark morphs is a strong candidate for Harlan's but I will have to review the photos. The larger concentrations were typically all juveniles, and the singles and pairs were typically adults. About 1/5 of the raptors also working "the gap" which is the flyway directly east of my location. The winds started out in the N/NW but moved more and more west as the day went on. Also completely sunny, not a cloud in the sky. Overall great movement and this is probably the last weekend of good hawk numbers before they rapidly decline for winter.

At first, I thought this might be a Rough-legged Hawk but realized it was a heavily marked Red-tail as I got closer.  Dark chocolate brown back with few if any light speckles, heavy splotches on the belly band and band was wider at the sides than in the middle, fairly dark throat with markings dribbling down to meet the belly band, warm buffy/rufous color on the breast above the belly band rather than the clean white of our normal borealis subspecies.  Slightly smaller than most of our red-tails and had a relatively small head.

Observation Details: A large hawk is dominating the fields of this park.  According to the park manager it is eating a lot of lizards.  I initially defaulted to juvenile red-shouldered, but the size and shape plus some ID marks like amount of white on chest above an obvious dark band and length of tail had me thinking possible RTHA.  After talking with local park birders F. Hoeflein and S. Juan, have changed to red-tailed.

Observation Details: I noticed a Heavy streaked breast, thick full belly band and dark hood on this bird. Compared to the other 2 clear eastern red tails nearby. Facebook group discussion with others much more knowledgeable of the subspecies than me  also concluded this bird was right for abieticola, so I am editing this observation to reflect this.

Locality: 21595 NW Sauvie Island Rd, Portland US-OR 45.68089, -122.86015
Observation Details: Uniformly dark brown above, heavily streaked on front. Tail white with dingy brown band (which I believe would make this an adult?) The white head threw me off. Originally thought it was an intermediate Harlan's, then thought Rough-legged Hawk but the tail doesn't seem right and it lacks the dark wrists of a light morph RLHA. Tarsi are visible, they don't appear feathered but hard to tell for sure - viewing conditions weren't much better because of the rain.

My first thought was a dark Western or Harlan’s.  After looking at my photos: -- Overall the bird appears not black, but brownish black with some noticeably (even in the bad pics) tawny tones about the head. -- The leg feathering is generally dark, with a splotchy pattern of alternating bands of brownish black and white.  Based on "Wheeler," I believe this alone rules out heavily marked Eastern RTHA as well as dark Rough-legged Hawk (also, wingtips do not reach tip of tail). -- Breast is white with heavy, coarse dark streaking. -- Tawny patch behind eye; contrastingly lighter auricular; no white eyebrow; eye appears pale. -- Undertail coverts white with thick dark barring. -- White mottled scapulars.  Reference: 1.  "Birds of Prey of the West," Wheeler. 2.  "ID Guide Raptors," Crossley. 3.  Thanks to Vic Berardi for feedback.  Update 11/14/21:  I've been having second thoughts about the ID of this hawk and decided to change it (from Western).  I think I originally put too much emphasis on the few tawny tones I can see on the head.  Overall, the bird is much too blackish looking; the breast is strongly marked with heavy white streaking; the leg feathers don't have any tawny tones; there is extensive contrastingly white spotting on the upper parts.  Liguori and Sullivan say "Most Harlan's...show blackish brown plumage with white streaked breast..."  And most of the Harlan's field guide pictures, and various photos on the WWW, including the eBird species gallery, are much better matches for this hawk.

Observation Details: Dark brown head/hood, dark brown neck/throat, dark brown dribbles down on to chest from head/neck, buffy upper chest with streaking, wide belly band - very wide along flanks. Fits the description and photos of Jon Ruddy: "Typical examples of abieticola show a noticeably dark head in which streaks “dribble” out from the sides of the throat and onto the upper breast, deep brown back (on average, noticeably darker than typical borealis), and extensive belly band composed of globular streaks which, in some individuals, forms a solid band which is “pinched in” at the center, and grows in width towards the flanks. The base color, especially throughout the upper breast, is more buffy/orange-toned in coloration than what is seen with typical borealis Red-taileds." https://ebird.org/canada/news/identifying-northern-red-tailed-hawks/

It eventually launched itself and flew down to the ground only 20'-25' from where I stood. It stayed on the ground for less than 30 seconds then flew back up into the tree from which it had come, with prey in its talon. It proceeded to eat what appeared to be a vole.

Wing-tagged, orange with black lettering "F/J". Reported to "wingtaggedhawks@portseattle.org. Also reported to the Federal Bird Banding Lab. Carole Hallett, the bander, provided info on this individual: "The wing tagged red-tail that you recently spotted was caught at PDX in December 2019 as part of an ongoing effort to reduce the incidence of bird-airplane collisions at the airport. It was released out in Tillamook County. Yours is the first reported resighting since release. The bird is likely a female based on measurements. She was only a second-year (hatched the previous year) when she was caught, so 2021 was likely the first year that she really had a shot at successful nesting."

Adult light morph Harlan's or light morph Harlan's intergrade that has been wintering in this area for the last couple of years. Photographed. Like a couple of other similar birds here in Crockett County that I also believe are light morph Harlan's intergrades, this bird looks spot on for a light morph Harlan's with the possible exception of the tail. It's hard to see in these distant pics but the tail of this bird is lighter at the base and more reddish towards the distal end with some banding. Otherwise the bird is very cold toned - snow white below, almost black above, with black, blobby belly band and blackish patagials. This hawk also has a lot of white on the head and face, typical of many Harlan's.

Beat the city high count (again)! All birds were tallied and were double checked to make sure they were separate individuals (the locals were seen over 15 times). Highlights were one dark juvenile seen early and a dark adult was seen really late (RTHA #50!). Mostly came in singles but there was a few kettles of two and three. Nice to see some substantial late season movement. Apparently, per Eli, this late push is due to birds from western Canada.
